________________________________________
1. “Linear time” means: superpositions evolve without distortion
Linearity is the statement:
[ U(t)(\alpha \psi + \beta \phi) = \alpha U(t)\psi + \beta U(t)\phi. ]
This is the superposition principle applied to time evolution.
What this guarantees physically
•	If a system can be in state A or state B, it can also be in any superposition of them.
•	The evolution of the superposition is exactly the superposition of the evolutions.
•	No cross terms, no nonlinear mixing, no weird distortions.

Why RCFT needs this
RCFT architecture is built on:
•	indivisible stochastic processes,
•	refinement steps,
•	probability amplitudes,
•	symplectic memory,
•	mass emerging from misalignment.
All of that collapses if time evolution is nonlinear.
Linearity is the bare minimum structure needed for quantum like behavior.
________________________________________
2. “Unitary time” means: probability and inner products are preserved
Unitarity is the statement:
[ U(t)^\dagger U(t) = I. ]
This means:
•	Norms are preserved
[ |\psi| = |U(t)\psi|. ]
•	Inner products are preserved
[ \langle \psi, \phi \rangle = \langle U(t)\psi, U(t)\phi \rangle. ]
What this guarantees physically
•	Total probability stays 1.
•	Orthogonality stays orthogonality.
•	Distinguishable states remain distinguishable.
•	No faster than light signaling.
•	No “manual renormalization” step.
•	No collapse of the symplectic memory structure.

Why RCFT needs this
The RCFT mass mechanism depends on the symplectic pairing:
[ \Omega(h,v). ]
If time evolution were not unitary, then:
•	the Higgs vector could “tilt,”
•	orthogonality could be lost,
•	massless directions could become massive,
•	the stabilizer subgroup could break,
•	the informational lane would distort.
Unitarity is what keeps the Higgs vector fixed, the mass mechanism stable, and the internal symmetries intact.
________________________________________
3. Why “linear + unitary” is the only consistent choice for RCFT
The Parker paper referenced makes a crucial point:
•	In Formulation A (normalized states),
linear ⇒ unitary automatically.
•	In Formulation B (projective states),
linear ≠ unitary,
and we get new physics (FTL signaling, etc.).

RCFT implicitly uses Formulation A, because:
•	RCFT uses normalized states,
•	RCFT uses Born probabilities directly,
•	RCFT requires probability conservation,
•	RCFT requires symplectic memory preservation,
•	RCFT requires no FTL signaling,
•	RCFT requires stable mass emergence.

So RCFT must adopt:
Linear time evolution
(to preserve superposition)
and therefore automatically:
Unitary time evolution
(to preserve probability and symplectic structure).
This is not an extra assumption — it’s a logical consequence of our architecture.
________________________________________
4. The intuitive picture
Think of time evolution in RCFT as a rotation in a very high dimensional space:
•	Linearity says the rotation acts the same on every part of a superposition.
•	Unitarity says the rotation preserves lengths and angles.
Together, they mean:
Time is a symmetry transformation of the informational space that preserves both superposition and probability.

This is exactly what we want for a theory where:
•	mass = misalignment with a fixed symplectic direction,
•	internal symmetries = stabilizer of that direction,
•	null directions = SO(9) sector,
•	gauge groups = boundary projections.
If time evolution distorted the geometry, none of this would hold.
________________________________________

RCFT adopts a refinement time operator that is linear (preserves superposition) and therefore unitary (preserves probability and the symplectic memory structure). 
This ensures that the Higgs vector remains fixed, massless directions remain orthogonal, and internal symmetries remain stable under time evolution.






