############



Core idea
•	Bulk: (Sp(8)\times SO(9)), refinement time, generator (H).
•	Boundary: SM gauge group, Higgs quartic (\lambda(Q_0)), effective (H_{\mathrm{SM}}(\mu)).
The Boundary Projection Principle is the rule that:
Only those bulk structures that admit a consistent, symmetry preserving, RG compatible projection to the Standard Model boundary are physically admissible in RCFT.
It ties together:
•	the dual lane geometry,
•	the generator (H),
•	the stabilizer (\mathrm{Stab}(h)),
•	and the scalar constraint (\lambda(Q_0)=\lambda_\star).
________________________________________
Boundary Projection Principle (RCFT). 
Let (H) be an admissible RCFT generator acting on the Hilbert space representation of the dual lane configuration space, with bulk symmetry (Sp(8)\times SO(9)) and fixed Higgs memory direction (h\in V). A bulk configuration ((H, \rho, h)) is physically admissible only if there exists a boundary projection [ \Pi: \mathcal{H} \to \mathcal{H}_{\mathrm{SM}} ] such that:
1.	Symmetry projection: 
[ \Pi, \rho(M), \Pi^\dagger = \rho_{\mathrm{SM}}(M_{\mathrm{proj}}) \qquad \forall, M\in\mathrm{Stab}(h), ] for some homomorphic image (M_{\mathrm{proj}}) in the Standard Model gauge group.
2.	Hamiltonian projection: 
[ H_{\mathrm{SM}}(\mu) = \Pi, H(\mu), \Pi^\dagger ] defines an effective Standard Model Hamiltonian at all (\mu < Q_0).
3.	Boundary scalar consistency: 
The projected scalar sector satisfies [ \lambda(Q_0) = \lambda_\star \approx -0.09538, ] and reproduces the observed Higgs mass under Standard Model RG flow.
4.	Phenomenological compatibility: 
The projected Hamiltonian (H_{\mathrm{SM}}(\mu)) is consistent with known low energy observables (masses, couplings, and symmetries) within the accuracy of the effective description.
Any bulk configuration that fails to admit such a projection is excluded as physically inadmissible in RCFT.
________________________________________
Why this matters
•	It closes the loop: bulk (H) is not just constrained abstractly, it is constrained by the existence of a consistent SM boundary.
•	It turns the SM into a consistency filter on RCFT, not an add on.
•	It makes your scalar constraint (\lambda(Q_0)=-0.09538) part of a general rule, not a one off calculation.





